[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This furniture animation effect is something that every single real estate videographer needs in their arsenal. This effect is perfect for filming those empty houses and making those videos just that much more engaging. Plus, if you\'re filming older, uglier homes, this'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effect also works to completely renovate and transform those houses to show future clients what that house could look like. And unlike some of my other videos, this tutorial is going to be completely beginner-friendly, so anyone'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can do it. But if you really want to take it up and upgrade the look, we are going to be using some pro techniques that\'s just going to polish the effect. And speaking of techniques, we\'re doing this inside of DaVinci Resolve, but you'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can do this in any editing platform that you might use. Just follow along and you\'ll be good, I promise. So if it\'s not already apparent that we\'re using AI to accomplish this effect, that\'s actually a really good thing because that means it\'s sort of hidden in plain'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sight for you. Now, the effect is pretty simple, but it does take some specific steps to get to the end result. So inside of DaVinci Resolve here, I have my clip. It is a simple push forward inside of the shot. Now, the more simple'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the camera movement, the better because then the AI has to do less guesswork. Now, to start up, we want to just trim this to sort of the start and end frame that we want to use for this animation. So to start, I actually like this start'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame right here. Now, let\'s scrub forward and I just want to show this whole living room, so I\'m probably going to cut it right around there. And this clip here, I already have pre-graded, so it is color-graded and you want to do this before that you send it to the AI.'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So the very first thing that you want to do is you want to grab a frame from the start and the end. So I\'m going to go into the color page to do that. I\'m going to make sure that I\'m located on my first frame of the clip. I\'m going to grab still, then I\'m going to go to the last frame of the clip and grab another'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still. And with each of these, I\'m going to export them with the display LUT. And we\'re going to be using Higgsfield to accomplish this effect. But first, we need to actually render a new image because doing it all in one video step is going to be nearly impossible and'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re not going to get good results. So first, we\'re going to go into the image tab and we\'re going to go into Nano Banana to start editing some image. So let\'s open up the new file, so let\'s go to our folder where we located them. And'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we want to go to our last frame of the video. So in this case, it\'s the closer frame, which is this guy right here. I\'m going to open that up. So for my prompt, I\'m going to type in furnish living room with modern furniture including a sectional rug, coffee table, light'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fixture, and two accent chairs. Add greenery to the shelves and make everything proportional to the room. All the furniture should be modern and cozy in style. Then I\'m going to hit generate. Here are the results that it'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gave me. Now, it\'s quite good, but it\'s not very good. We have some inconsistencies that we\'re going to have to work with. Obviously, the layout of this room is not correct right now. We\'d want the couch to be facing the TV. We don\'t want a light fixture in the'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ceiling. I was more meaning a little lamp stand. But for the rest, it did a pretty good job. But we\'re going to have to redo this because that is not what we\'re going for. So I\'ve done some iterations and they just didn\'t quite work out for me. So this one, the furniture was placed in the wrong'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction. The second time, these two uh were pretty close, but this one has a lamp right in front of the stairwell and the door. This one, the TV is hanging too low and I actually decided I don\'t want a piano and there\'s not enough walking space here. Same thing with this'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. This one is pretty close, but the TV is a little bit too low and these chairs are just placed a little bit awkwardly. So the final result for the final prompt that I\'m going to input here is furnish living room with modern'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'furniture including sectional rug, coffee table, stand-alone lamp, and two accent chairs. Add greenery to the shelves and make everything proportional to the room. All the furniture should be modern and cozy in style and make the'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'living room centered and facing the fireplace and add a TV to the TV bracket. Remove the piano in the room. The furniture should not be too close to the kitchen counter on the right of the frame and the accent stand-alone lamp should be in the back left corner of the'

[03:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'room. Now, let\'s hit generate. And now in this case, I think the result that we got right here is a really good result. We have all the furniture, it looks quite realistic. There\'s a healthy amount of walking room around this living room and it doesn\'t look too'

[03:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cluttered. So let\'s download this as a PNG just like so. Now, let\'s actually turn this into a moving animated video. So to do that, let\'s go into the video tab and go into create video. Now, in my experience, using Kling has actually'

[04:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'been the best model to use for this effect and it\'s given me pretty consistent results. So we\'re going to add a start frame and we\'re going to open the wider shot, which is this guy right here, and we\'re going to open that up. Then add an end frame and select the'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'furnished room that we have just created. Then as far as the prompt goes, I have each piece of furniture that pops up and falls into place one by one. That is super important to write, you have to write one by one. The camera has super'

[04:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smooth forward motion. And that just makes sure that the motion of the camera is super smooth. Again, I\'m going to be using Kling 2.1 because that gives me the best results. I\'m setting the duration to 5 seconds. You don\'t want this to be too long. And the resolution,'

[04:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'obviously, the highest it can go, which is 1080p. Now, let\'s hit generate. And it\'s just finished generating. Let\'s take a look at this result. Oof. That is not very good. Now, obviously,'

[04:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this result is not really what we\'re looking for. We got some weird furniture sliding across the room, morphed into different chairs, and then this TV just rises up super, super slowly. The rest of it is okay,'

[05:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'um but that does not look very good. It looks really jarbled and messy. All right, so after trying a couple different styles and prompts, uh I\'ve landed on each piece of furniture pops in, rotates, and falls into place one by'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. The camera has super smooth forward motion. Now, I\'ve tried more complex prompts down below, but the results just didn\'t really get any better. So you\'re probably just going to have to generate it a couple times to get the desired'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'result you\'re after. But a really good starting place is to be using the prompt that I have right there. Then I\'m going to take the clip that I like the most and I\'m going to download it. Now, let\'s go back into DaVinci Resolve, back into the edit page, and import that new clip'

[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ve just generated inside of our downloads folder. Now, let\'s take that and drag it onto the timeline. And you can see that the length of time is quite a bit slower than our original clip because we\'ve slowed it down to 5'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'seconds, which is just going to feel a little bit slow. So I\'m actually going to speed it up to the exact same clip before. And now if we take a look at this, we can see we have this cool furniture animation in this shot. And this is cool and all, but we need to'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take this a step further because we need to blend it into our original footage. I want to speed ramp into a shot, then have the furniture animate onto the screen, and then speed ramp at the end of that clip again. And I\'m going to'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'show you how to do that right now. So in this case, we\'re going to do it with this dining room shot right here. So you can start see that we start right here in the dining room and then we pull back over top of this counter and we have a pretty long clip. So let\'s set the out'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point right there. Let\'s drag that onto the timeline and let\'s reverse this clip. And if we take a look at this, we want to just speed ramp the start to right around there. So I\'m going to hit control R, add a speed point, and speed up the first portion of the clip. And'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now I\'m going to slow the rest to 50%. Now, I\'m going to hit this keyframes button right here and open the keyframe curves and drag this up so I can view it a little bit better. We\'re going to ease out this speed ramping by hitting ease'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in and out, dragging this out, and then holding shift to ease it out a little bit further. But I don\'t want to go all the way to the end. I want to do it about halfway through this 50% portion of the clip. So now that we have our speed ramped clip, we have to decide'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what our start and end frame of the animation is going to be. So to start, I think the animation should start maybe right around there. And we want to make sure that this footage is already moving as slow as possible. That\'s why I didn\'t'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ease it all the way to the end of the clip to make sure that we can place our generated clip at the exact same point in time, we\'re going to press M while selecting the timeline so that we have a marker placed. Now, I want this motion to maybe be a little bit further, so I\'m'

[07:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually going to extend this out and it can be right to the end of the clip. So with our playhead above the marker, let\'s go to the color page, grab a still. Now, let\'s go to the last frame of this clip and grab another still. Now again, with both of these, let\'s just'

[08:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'export them. And we\'re going to go through the exact same process, but I\'m just going to speed through this a little bit faster. So again, you\'re going to first generate that second image. So I\'m going to go to smart image editing. I\'m going to upload'

[08:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'my new photo, which is the closer version of the dining room. And for furnishing this room, I have written furnish dining room with modern furniture including a table, chairs, and stand-alone light in the corner of the'

[08:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'room. All of the furniture should be modern and cozy in style and make the table oriented so the length is from left to right. Let\'s hit generate. And now take your generated image and download it. Go into video, replace the two frames, and add the start frame,'

[08:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is the wider shot of the dining room. Then add the generated image as the last frame. You can keep the prompt the same and hit generate. All right, and if we take a look at this generation, our very first generation here is actually quite good. I like the'

[08:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little touch of the plate falling in at the last second. So let\'s go ahead and download that. Now, back inside of DaVinci Resolve, we need to line this up perfectly. So let\'s first import our new clip and let\'s drag it onto the'

[09:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'timeline. Now, we know that it needs to start right there. And to roughly match the speed of the clip, it should be ending right about there. Because now if we were to turn the opacity down, you can see that the locations of the clip'

[09:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty much line up perfectly because we\'ve kept the exact same speed of the clip, which is important because something that drives me nuts with AI-generated videos is generally you see this swooping realistic camera angle and'

[09:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then the AI video starts and it\'s swooping in and then it stops and then it starts moving again because AI-generated videos don\'t know the speed or momentum of the camera before the video actually takes place. But if you'

[09:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do it this way and time it up with the exact same clip that you already used, you get a way better result. But you can cheat it a little bit and go a little bit slower, and that\'s actually what I\'m going to do right here. So I\'m going to'

[09:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drag this out and speed because I want to be able to have some clip to speed ramp at the end of the footage. And as you can see, even with slightly slower footage, you still get really smooth transition from the original shot right here to the'

[10:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI-generated shot. So, we could maybe even slow it down a little bit more just like so, and we still get smooth motion, and we can make this even a little bit smoother with using some AI inside of DaVinci Resolve. But first, let\'s add'

[10:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some speed ramping. So, at the end here, maybe right around there where most of the animation is done happening, I\'m going to speed up the end of that clip, and I\'m going to hold Alt and the down key to drag it back down onto the'

[10:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original track, and then it speeds up right at the end. Perfect. So, now let\'s open the keyframe editor again with the retime curves, and let\'s just adjust this curve like so, holding Shift to drag out the start. There we go, and now'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ve got a little speed ramp right at the end, but I can still see the transition in between the two clips. Obviously, because the resolution gets a little bit lower, but to fix the resolution, obviously, we can just go to AI super scale, and now increase it back'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up to 4K from that 1080 rendered image. But to make this transition as smooth as possible, I\'m going to go into the effects, go into video transitions, and add a smooth cut. I\'m going to drag it a little bit shorter because once the'

[11:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actual furniture animation starts, I don\'t want that smooth cut transition to still be happening because that\'s going to look real weird. So, the table comes up right there. So, I want it to keep animating until the table starts coming'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up. So, maybe right there. So, now our end result is we have a speed ramped clip, and then it seamlessly transitions into artificial footage, and then speed ramps out again. So, it\'s absolutely crazy that you can make these types of furniture animations for your real'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'estate videos in just seconds. This type of animation in the past probably would have taken hours, if not days, to create. So, this is an absolute time-saver. And speaking of time, there\'s another tool that can save you'

[11:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an incredible amount of time, and that\'s Opus Clip, today\'s video sponsor. If you make long-form content like I do, you know how incredibly long it takes to turn that into short-form content like for Instagram Reels, or for YouTube'

[12:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shorts, or for TikToks, but Opus Clip does that all for you, and all that you need is a YouTube link. So, you don\'t even need the original video. It automatically finds the best and most engaging moments of your video. It edits them for you. It reframes them. It adds'

[12:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'captions. It can add AI-generated B-roll, or just stock B-roll, and it even gives you a virality score to tell you which of your videos are more likely to perform better. And it doesn\'t stop there. If you want full control and full'

[12:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'customization, they have a fully fledged video editor inside of their platform. So, you can still adjust the framing. You can adjust the captions. You can adjust the pacing. You can literally adjust everything about the clip. But instead of starting from scratch, you'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty much get a nearly perfect short already, and then you can just make your final tweaks right at the end. So, what used to take hours now literally only takes minutes. So, if you want to be consistent across all of your platforms like Instagram, TikTok, and YouTube'

[12:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shorts, make sure that you check out Opus Clip. Not only will you save time, but you\'ll also grow faster. Now, there is a link down below in the description that gets you one free week of Opus Clip plus 50% off for three entire months so that you can try out Opus Clip and start'

[13:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saving time. All right, back to the video. And now let\'s switch things up a little bit, and let\'s renovate an old home into a new home. But we want to make sure that proportions and everything stay super similar so that we\'re actually showing the client what'

[13:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the house could realistically look like. So, in this case, let\'s use this kitchen as an example. So, this is an older home with obviously an older outdated kitchen, but the space itself is not that bad. So, we want to show what it'

[13:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'could actually look like. So, let\'s drag that clip onto the timeline. Let\'s choose our start frame, which I think this wide frame right here is pretty good. We can start there and end right around there, still showing the entire'

[13:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kitchen. Now, in the color page, let\'s grab the first still, and let\'s grab the last still, or the last frame. Let\'s export both of those. Now, we need to go back to the image editor and open Nano Banana. And in this case, let\'s actually'

[13:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reverse the motion that we\'ve been doing before. So, in both of the other clips, we\'ve been pushing forward into the shot. In this case, let\'s just switch it up so you can see it works both ways. So, let\'s take the wider shot of the two, open that, and now we are going to'

[14:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'renovate this. So, the prompt that I\'m using to renovate this kitchen is renovate the kitchen to be modern and minimal. Keep the exact same proportions of the room and replace the appliances with new stainless steel versions, but'

[14:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keep the location and size the same. Change the cabinets out for modern white cabinets, and make the counter and backsplash marble. Paint the walls white, and replace the floor with warm vinyl plank flooring, and replace the'

[14:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dining room furniture with new furniture in the same location. Add modern lights to the ceiling. Now that these four generations are done, let\'s take a look at our options. Now, you can do this as many times as you want. You can also change it to unlimited so that it\'s'

[14:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'completely free, but it\'s a little bit faster when you pay one credit, which is not a whole lot. And if we take a look at all of these four generations, they all have something different going for them. So, this one looks all right, but the flooring is not replaced, and the'

[15:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'appliances are still the same. This one, the oven moved all the way over to the right, which is something that we don\'t want. Uh this one is pretty good. I just don\'t like that this cabinet in the middle here, the island, is still the'

[15:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original oak. Uh and then this one here looks like our best option. The lights look quite good. Uh the table wasn\'t replaced, but that\'s okay cuz we\'re mostly focused on the kitchen right now. So, let\'s go ahead and download that. Now, let\'s go into video, create video,'

[15:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and for the start frame, we\'re going to actually pick the closer up frame because again, we\'re going to be moving backwards in this case. So, I\'m going to open that, and then for the last frame, now we\'re going to use the AI-generated image, which is this guy right here. So,'

[15:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is the prompt that we\'re going with. It\'s the room renovates itself piece by piece, and individual elements pop up and fall into place while the floor rolls out new vinyl plank. There is super smooth backwards camera motion. Now, let\'s hit generate. All right, and'

[15:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'once your AI-generated video is done, you\'re going to hit download. Now, import that clip and drag it onto the timeline. And again, let\'s drag it up above the original shot and increase the speed just like so. And now you can see'

[16:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we have this awesome AI renovation sequence that looks absolutely incredible. But again, if we want to speed ramp this within the same clip, we can still do that even though we didn\'t do it to the original clip. So, to do'

[16:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that, all that we need to do is we need to extend the start of the bottom layer, which is the original shot, because this keeps the rest of the clip the exact same. So, we\'re going to start right there, and as you can see, it'

[16:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transitions to the animated shot still perfectly, even though we extended the bottom clip. But we want to make sure that that frame doesn\'t change, so let\'s just cut the clip right there. Now, let\'s hit Ctrl R and open up this clip.'

[16:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s add a speed point right here, and let\'s extend this to 50% speed. And now you can see we\'re still smoothly transitioning into our renovation shot. We can slow down this renovation shot a'

[16:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit as well, and let\'s just drag this forward just a little bit here so that we have less of that slow footage, and let\'s speed up the start of that clip. Maybe something like so, but I still think that this is a little bit'

[17:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'too long. But we don\'t want to trim this up because now we\'re changing the end frame. So, we only want to adjust the actual speed ramping. So, I\'m going to drag that in right there, and the difference is is this is just pulling'

[17:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that end frame closer to the speed ramp. It\'s not actually changing the frame that we\'re transitioning on. Let\'s increase the speed again a little bit of the start transition. Now, let\'s open that in the keyframe editor and smooth out that speed ramp. And if we take a'

[17:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at that, we have a nice smooth speed ramp that transitions into our AI renovation shot. Let\'s make that still a little bit smoother by adding a smooth cut. Just again, as short as possible, just like so, and we\'ve got a seamless'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transition. And now let\'s just speed ramp the end of this clip so it finishes renovating right roughly around here, but I\'m going to go back a couple frames and add another speed point, and I\'m going to increase the end speed of this'

[17:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clip. Again, opening the keyframe panel and the curves to smooth that out further just like so. As you can probably tell, these speed ramps are not super drastic because we don\'t have that much footage to work with. So, we can'

[18:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enhance that by just adding an adjustment clip over top of this. So, let\'s grab an adjustment clip from our effects panel right over there. Drag that over the timeline. Now, let\'s open the fusion page. Hit Shift Space, and hit XF, and that\'s going to open a'

[18:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transform node. Let\'s set a keyframe on size at the start. Now, let\'s set another keyframe on size at the end, but let\'s zoom it out a bit just like so. Now, let\'s make sure that we change the edges from canvas to mirror, and you\'re going to go up top right here and click'

[18:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the spline editor. Then, with the transform selected, hit zoom to fit. Hit Ctrl A to grab all of the keyframes, and hit S, and we just want to reverse this sort of just like so so that now it\'s really zooming out right at the end of'

[18:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the clip, just like we\'re simulating a speed ramp. And if we loop these clips up just like so, we have the smooth transition between the two clips. We have the speed ramped clip, and that transitions into the AI-generated footage. We need to add some motion blur'

[19:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to sort of smooth that out a little bit. So, I\'m just dragging my motion blur over top of my timeline and dragging that between the cut, making sure that that is centered up right nicely, just like so. And as you can see, that just'

[19:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'adds a whole \'nother level of smoothness to the clips. So, if you want some of the best motion blur in the game, make sure that you check out the link down below in the description, and you can get it for yourself. Okay, and here are my sort of rules or tips and tricks to'

[19:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get the best AI generations possible to make your real estate edits pop and look a whole lot better than they are. So, number one, and I\'d say probably the most important, is the word proportional. And this is specifically'

[19:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talking about the image generations that we\'re going to be doing, is when I use the word proportional in my prompt, I 99% of the time always get a better end result. So, let\'s say renovate this kitchen but keep everything proportional'

[19:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the original layout or add furniture to this living room proportional to the size of the living room. It just works a whole lot better than saying like renovate this kitchen but keep it the same. AI doesn\'t really understand that but the word proportional specifically'

[20:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'does help a lot. Now, for number two, always feed the AI the highest generation image that you can. So, my clips are 4K but if I\'m working on a 1080p timeline and grab a still, I\'m only getting a 1080p image. So, make'

[20:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sure you switch that up to 4K, then grab your image, input that into the AI and the AI is actually not going to give you the same resolution back but the more information that you give the AI, the better your end result is going to be'

[20:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the better the overall detail of the image will be. And for number three, just keep the camera movement simple. So, I\'ve tried to do some tilting, sort of orbiting shots up some stairs and the AI just doesn\'t fully understand that'

[20:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera motion because the angles are just so completely different. Whereas if you just have a straight push or you have an orbit, the AI can sort of interpolate that and be able to guess what\'s in between those frames because it sees everything already. Especially'

[20:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with a push, everything that it needs to generate is sort of already in the frame. Obviously, it needs to add some parallax but it can do a push or an orbit pretty well but it can\'t seem to do these crazy tilts or just movements that are too far in between because then'

[21:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it has to guess what\'s happening in between those frames and what the backside of furniture and such looks like and that\'s when you get some really bad results. And number four is specifically about prompting. I found that telling the AI what to do is not'

[21:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the best approach. Rather, maybe this seems sort of obvious but all you want to do is describe your scene. So, you don\'t want to say animate the furniture so that it pops in one by one. You want to say the furniture animates and pops'

[21:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in one by one. So, you\'re describing the scene as is rather than telling the AI how to animate the scene. So, let\'s say for this example, we have the room renovates itself piece by piece,'

[21:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'individual elements pop up and fall into place. So, that\'s a good way of prompting it. Rather if I said renovate this room piece by piece and make individual elements pop up and fall into place. Now, I just added a bunch of'

[21:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'words that the AI can\'t process properly and again, you get a worse result. So, just strictly describe your scene rather than giving it filler words and telling the AI what to do. And for the next tip, you sort of have to find the balance of'

[22:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how specific to be. So, one thing I\'ve noticed is if you write let\'s say add modern flooring to this home, it\'s pretty much always going to add a gray vinyl plank. And the reason is that was a trend for the longest time. Vinyl'

[22:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plank is still a trend but gray not so much anymore. So, if you want warm vinyl plank, then you have to write warm tone vinyl plank or something similar to that. Sometimes when you\'re too generic with a word like modern, then it goes back a couple years to what used to be'

[22:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'modern or what it thinks is still modern because there\'s so much data on it, it\'ll generate that instead of what\'s actually current. But on the flip side, if you start being way too crazy specific, then it just turns out to be a'

[22:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'jarble and the AI doesn\'t really know what to do. So, it\'s a balance of making a generation and if you see that it is following a certain trend, let\'s say the gray flooring, it\'s always doing gray flooring, I know that I\'m going to write warm tone vinyl plank because I don\'t'

[23:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want gray flooring, I want brown flooring for like a light oak type of texture. But yeah, it\'s really just about finding a balance between being too specific and not specific enough. Also, I hate to break it to you but with AI, you are going to have to do multiple'

[23:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generations because as you saw in this video, I was pretty honest about it, you don\'t get success the very first time you generate. So, often you\'ll have to do multiple generations and often you don\'t actually have to change the prompt in between generations. You can just'

[23:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click generate again and you\'ll probably get a better result the second time or a different result that might suit your needs a little bit better. So, sometimes I actually even generate a shorter or lower resolution video than what I want just to sort of test out a prompt to see'

[23:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what it gives me in the end result. And then if that prompt gets me close to where I want to be, that\'s when I turn up the model to a higher resolution and a longer length. That way I save some credits and I can still experiment with'

[23:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new prompts. And then lastly, we already talked about it in this video but make sure that the speed of your AI generation matches the speed of your actual real footage because having that jarring speed difference between real'

[24:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'footage and an AI clip instantly signals my brain and probably everyone else\'s brain that now you\'re watching AI footage. But if you speed ramp into a room and are playing at 50% speed, make sure that that clip afterwards is'

[24:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'playing in the same speed relative to the actual real footage. So, I think I showed it pretty well in the tutorial but just make sure that the speed lines up because that\'s going to match it through a whole lot smoother and obviously add the smooth cut transition as well to increase the smoothness of'

[24:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that. And oh, one more thing, pretty much every AI generation is going to be 1080p. So, always use the AI upscaler inside of DaVinci Resolve to bring that back up to 4K to get a higher resolution image. Okay, so this video is obviously'

[24:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a little bit different than my normal DaVinci Resolve content but let me know down below in the comments if you liked it and if you want to see more of it. Is this something that you could use for yourself in your real estate videos? I think it is. I think it is a pretty neat'

[24:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effect. But thank you guys so much for tuning in. Thank you as well to Opus Clip for sponsoring this video and as always, Jesus loves you. See you.'
